      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "Careful with the terms mod and modular because n (mod m) IS ALWAYS &gt;= 0 but not n % m. n % m is in the range &gt; -m and &lt; m. Although Java has a remainder operator for int and long types, it has no modulus function or operator. I.e., -12 % 10 = -2 whereas -12 mod 10 = 8. If % operator returns a negative value for n % m, then (n % m) + m will give you n mod m. BigInteger provides functions for both and the specifications for them explain the difference quite well. Also, careful with zero. In mathematics, whilst zero is an even number it is NOT positive or negative."
