      "comment_id" : 137059158,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "If you really need to handle huge numbers, you can cast to a larger type: (int) (((long) a % b + b) % b). Alternatively, if you&#39;re on Java 8+, you can simply use Math.floorMod(a, b)."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1761703,
      "reputation" : 446,
      "user_id" : 2802543,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11184c8266241679b87bd5f772b0ff6a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Dayanto",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2802543/dayanto"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 14,
    "last_activity_date" : 1704337662,
    "last_edit_date" : 1704337662,
    "creation_date" : 1379782690,
    "answer_id" : 18935194,
    "question_id" : 90238,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>While it's possible to do a proper modulo by checking whether the value is negative and correct it if it is (the way many have suggested), there is a more compact solution.</p>\n<pre><code>(a % b + b) % b\n</code></pre>\n<p>This will first take the remainder, limiting the value to the -b -&gt; +b range and then add b in order to ensure that the value is positive, letting the next remainder limit it to the 0 -&gt; b range.</p>\n<p>Note: If b is negative, the result will also be negative.</p>\n<p><strong>Edit</strong>: Since Java 8, you should probably be using Math.floorMod(a,b) instead. Be aware that floorMod() has the same quirk as my solution in that it returns negative values if b is negative.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3755950,
      "reputation" : 1206,
      "user_id" : 3122309,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/kmQWW.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "brothers28",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3122309/brothers28"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1399902261,
    "creation_date" : 1399902261,
    "answer_id" : 23610743,
    "question_id" : 90238,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Another way is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>boolean isEven = false;\nif((a % 2) == 0)\n{\n    isEven = true;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>But easiest way is still: </p>\n\n<pre><code>boolean isEven = (a % 2) == 0;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Like @Steve Kuo said.</p>\n"
  }, {
