      "creation_date" : 1578348828,
      "post_id" : 56878005,
      "comment_id" : 105402688,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Well not exactly... The javadoc of <code>Math.floorMod()</code> has it: <code>The floor modulus is x - (floorDiv(x, y) * y), has the same sign as the divisor y, and is in the range of -abs(y) &lt; r &lt; +abs(y).</code> So it is not exactly the same as mathematical modulus. <b>But</b>, there is a way to get a positive result, also in the Javadoc of the same method: <code>If the signs of arguments are unknown and a positive modulus is needed it can be computed as (floorMod(x, y) + abs(y)) % abs(y).</code>"
